[normal]2.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Although there has been welcomed progress, 
[normal]CCN believe that there is further scope for
[normal] fiscal devolution
[normal] in England
[normal], particularly in a
[normal]reas not already benefiting from City Deals.
[normal] 
[normal]It is clear from our engagement with member councils involved in the Second Wave of City Deals that 
[normal]Deals
[normal] were considerably less ambitious than those offered to the Core Cities in the First Wave, with significan
[normal]tly less powers, funding and flexibilities available to areas. As one CCN member council told us, ‘
[normal]our City Deal is unfortunately rather devoid of any fiscal devolution measures’.  
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We share the LGA’s view that the LGF fail
[normal]s
[normal] to 
[normal]grasp
[normal] the ambition set out
[normal] in the Heseltine Review, with the 
[normal]limited £2bn 
[normal]p/a 
[normal]funding simply 
[normal]a reallocation of existing council
[normal] resources
[normal] or already-devolved funding.
[normal] Limited 
[normal]Whitehall 
[normal]funding and subsequent guidance leads us to the conclusion that Growth Deals do not represent 
[normal]the same fiscal devolution opportunities accorded to the Core Cities and City Reg
[normal]ions. This undoubtedly
[normal] creat
[normal]es
[normal] 
[normal]disadvantages for many
[normal] 
[normal]CCN member councils
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.7
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]CCN [bold]maintain [bold]that [bold]fiscal devolution has been [bold]narrowly [bold]focused on the Core Cities and City Regions[bold].
[normal] Whilst this 
[normal]is 
[normal]not a zero-sum game between cities and counties on who is better placed to implement fiscal devolution, t
[normal]here continues to be an uncritical acceptance of the view that groups of authorities serving large urban areas are more suited to devol
[normal]ution than counties. 
[normal]CCN 
[normal]strong
[normal]ly
[normal] dispute this.
[normal] 
[normal]Given the growth potential of county economies, and 
[normal]strategic
[normal] economic
[normal] role of our member councils
[normal], there is no barrier to broadly symmetrical devolution across England, 
[normal]potentially 
[normal]allowing more independence for, and innovation from, county councils and 
[normal]unitary counties
[normal] in England
[normal]. 
[normal]CCN therefore believe that alongside a more ambitiou
[normal]s approach to fiscal devolution
[normal], there
[normal] needs to be a thorough re-appraisal of the role of counties in 
[normal]promoting growth and implementing fiscal devolution.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.8
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
